<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/29#issuecomment-3194286125" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**2 :fas-comment:**
</div>

Here's a possible implementation that seems clean to me, atleast for Input Processing.

1) Have a common parent for all classes that will handle all exceptions
2) All other classes will propagate their errors to the parent (by rethrowing the errors, possibly create custom exceptions)
3) Handle errors at the parent, eg. print error message to CLI

Feel free to share any thoughts.
</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/29#issuecomment-3196385778" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**3 :fas-comment:**
</div>

> > Here's a possible implementation that seems clean to me, atleast for Input Processing.
> > 
> > 1. Have a common parent for all classes that will handle all exceptions
> > 2. All other classes will propagate their errors to the parent (by rethrowing the errors, possibly create custom exceptions)
> > 3. Handle errors at the parent, eg. print error message to CLI
> > 
> > Feel free to share any thoughts.
> 
> [@jovnc](https://github.com/jovnc) Does a "common parent" mean that the class will extend the exception handler?
> 
> To OP [@Ruinim](https://github.com/Ruinim) as well: My views are that although having a dedicated exception handler might be "cleaner", it could make the code less readable. i.e. the person reading the code does not get to see what exception is expected. (Just imagine, if you have 20 exceptions, how do you know for that part of the code which exception(s) might hit ?)
> 
> Of course, you could make it so that every exception is its own method which would reflect the expected exception. But then there is a separate issue of what if in different parts of your code you would want different behaviour for the same exception?
> 
> Also, handling exceptions ASAP instead of passing it on to the caller function so that your debug log is not messy.

Sorry, maybe using a wrong terminology here, as it can get confused with OOP inheritance. 

What I actually had in mind was something like having a main class responsible for input handling, which would also be the central place to catch and manage exceptions. That way, all the other classes can propagate their errors up to this class, and the decision for how to handle them (e.g., logging or printing error messages) is made in one place.

'''java
class A ``{``
    try ``{``
        // handle input here
    ``}`` catch (ExceptionA e) ``{``
        // centralized handling
    ``}`` catch (ExceptionB e) ``{``

    ``}``
``}``
'''

The idea is just to keep exception handling consistent by managing it in a central layer, rather than having every class deal with it separately.
</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/29#issuecomment-3198828603" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**4 :fas-comment:**
</div>

> https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/29#issuecomment-3196385778
> @jovnc 
> I see, I think my point about readability and having different behaviour for the same exception in different parts of the code would still apply as mentioned to OP
> 

I have considered that approach, and it definitely is sound. However, I had some troubles implementing that and thus stuck to the "global" exception handling approach.

Here's a a few things you might want to note when implementing that:
- how should you handle the exception in child classes? 
- eg. you have a handleTask function that uses a child class to parse the input string, create the task, etc. How should the child class propagate the error message up? Do you just crash the program, or should handleTask return an error message instead

I think it also ultimately depends on how you structure your program, to see which solution fits best for your use case.
</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/29#issuecomment-3200164053" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**5 :fas-comment:**
</div>

> I am curious, what troubles did you have with implementation?
> 
> As for the implementation, we should never crash the program. 
> As mentioned I would catch it in the callee, and then like you said, propagate an error message up.
> This way if the end user expects output, you could still see something general while not revealing too much of your backend like 
> "Error connecting with database, check your connection" 
> 
> I think it also goes beyond code and efficiency as I mentioned (and as such what you refer to as "which solution fits best for your use case")
> To me code readability is important especially when you are working in a team.
> For example in python, I would rather see a "normal" embedded for loop than a 3 tier list comprehension even if list comprehension is much more efficient. 
> 

I considered the implementation you mentioned, where I handle it in the child class, by returning a 'String' as an error message, instead of propagating the error up the hierarchy.

However, it seemed awkward to return a 'String' to me, as that's not what I would expect the function to return. From the 'parent' class point of view, it seems like there was no error to begin with (even though it should be an error, that is handled).

Furthermore, what if the error occurs in a class with a function that doesn't return a 'String'? eg. DateUtils to parse date strings, where the function should return LocalDate object.

But yes, I do agree that handling errors where it first occurs does seem cleaner in terms on thinking about the logic of it. I guess there are tradeoffs to each implementation.

</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/61#issuecomment-3216651668" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**6 :fas-comment:**
</div>

Hi, it appears that your tag for Level-5 and Level-6 does not belong to the `master` branch in your repository. Your previous tags do not have this issue, thus it can be picked up in iP dashboard page.

Level-5 tag:
<img width="954" height="525" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3fce562e-83af-4c1d-b944-874949eb11a4" />

Level-4 tag:
<img width="937" height="473" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3ce302e6-a5f9-4bf4-9e2b-d5cbec654a26" />

Here's the fix:
1. delete the tag locally

`git tag -d Level-5`

2. delete the tag from the remote

`git push origin --delete Level-5`

3. find the relevant commit you want to tag it

`git log --oneline`

4. tag the relevant commit

`git tag <COMMIT-HASH>`

5. push the tag

`git push origin Level-5`
</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/82#issuecomment-3231654111" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**7 :fas-comment:**
</div>

> I have shifted from using text-ui-test (input.txt and expected.txt) to JUnit for a more automated testing approach.
> 
> text-ui-test was useful before saving was implemented as there was no memory involved so outputs were always consistent. However, with the introduction of a file to save to and load from, it is more practical to utilize JUnit for future testing as it allows you to test individual features in a more stable and automated manner.

JUnit is useful for unit testing, ie. testing individual classes and methods. However, it cannot simulate entire user flows for proper integration / E2E testing, ie. to ensure that components interacts with each other as intended. Therefore, it is important to have both to ensure that your application is well tested.
</panel>

