<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/54#issuecomment-3210357244" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**3 :fas-comment:**
</div>

Consider using [Github Desktop](https://docs.github.com/en/desktop/installing-and-authenticating-to-github-desktop/authenticating-to-github-in-github-desktop) which will help manage credentials and all the different actions used in the course. 

Why is github desktop is your choice (Chatgpt to help):

* **GitHub Desktop handles login for you.**
  When you sign in through the app, it opens a web-based OAuth flow (your browser), then securely stores a token locally. This means you don’t need to deal with `git config credential.helper`, `ssh keys`, or `gh auth login` manually.

* **Behind the scenes:**
  GitHub Desktop still uses Git under the hood. Normally on the CLI you’d need to:

  * Set up **SSH keys** or
  * Configure a **personal access token (PAT)** for HTTPS.

  Desktop does this transparently by using the stored OAuth token whenever Git needs authentication.

* **Where it helps:**

  * No repeated username/password prompts.
  * No need to copy PATs or manage SSH keys manually.
  * Cross-platform (Windows/macOS/Linux) so it bypasses common OS credential manager headaches.

* **Where it doesn’t fully solve things:**

  * If you switch to command line Git outside of GitHub Desktop, you’ll still need to configure authentication (PAT/SSH) separately.
  * If you need advanced Git features (custom credential helpers, enterprise setups, automation), you’ll still have to touch the CLI.

👉 So: GitHub Desktop **solves authentication for itself** and makes Git "just work" in the GUI. But if you jump back into terminal Git, the Desktop login won’t automatically cover you unless your OS credential manager has synced with it.

</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/74#issuecomment-3231647916" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**4 :fas-comment:**
</div>

As @nty-dev has mentioned, personal access tokens can only be used for HTTPS Git operations. If your repository uses an SSH remote URL, you will need to [switch the remote from SSH to HTTPS](https://docs.github.com/en/get-started/git-basics/managing-remote-repositories#switching-remote-urls-from-ssh-to-https).

Also based on your operating system you could try the follow fix (Generated with chatgpt and the prompt below) :
'''prompt
Hi I tried following the instructions in https://se-education.org/guides/tutorials/sourcetree.html and https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/managing-your-personal-access-tokens#creating-a-personal-access-token-classic. I entered the username and PAT and received the message of "Authentication failed". I created a new PAT, reentered the username and new PAT and still received the message of "Authentication failed".
'''

## 🔹 Windows (SourceTree + GitHub PAT)

### Step 1: Clear old GitHub credentials

1. Open **Control Panel → Credential Manager**.
2. Go to **Windows Credentials**.
3. Find entries related to `github.com` (under *Generic Credentials*).
4. Remove them.

---

### Step 2: Make sure you’re using System Git

1. Open **SourceTree → Tools → Options → Git tab**.
2. Select **Use System Git** (not Embedded Git).
3. Apply and restart SourceTree.

---

### Step 3: Re-add GitHub account with PAT

1. In SourceTree, go to **Tools → Options → Authentication**.
2. Remove any old GitHub accounts.
3. Click **Add** → Choose *GitHub* → Choose *HTTPS*.
4. When prompted for username/password:

   * **Username** → your GitHub username (not email).
   * **Password** → your PAT.

If SourceTree rejects it, you can instead let Windows Credential Manager store it:

'''bash
git credential-manager-core erase
git credential-manager-core store
'''

and then retry push/pull once in SourceTree.

---

## 🔹 Mac (SourceTree + GitHub PAT)

### Step 1: Clear old GitHub credentials

1. Open **Keychain Access**.
2. Search for `github.com`.
3. Delete any entries.

---

### Step 2: Switch Git in SourceTree

1. Open **SourceTree → Preferences → Git**.
2. Select **System Git**.
3. Restart SourceTree.

---

### Step 3: Re-add GitHub account with PAT

1. Go to **SourceTree → Preferences → Accounts**.
2. Remove any old GitHub entries.
3. Add a new one:

   * Hosting Service: **GitHub**
   * Protocol: **HTTPS**
   * Authentication: **Basic**
   * Username: your GitHub username
   * Password: your **PAT**

If SourceTree refuses to accept the PAT in GUI, you can set it via terminal:

'''bash
git credential-osxkeychain erase
git credential-osxkeychain store
'''

and then retry push/pull in SourceTree.

---

## 🔹 Quick sanity check (works on both)

Before retrying SourceTree, confirm your PAT works in terminal:

'''bash
git ls-remote https://github.com/username/repo.git
'''

* Enter username → GitHub username
* Enter password → PAT

If that succeeds, SourceTree should also succeed once credentials are cleared and reset.

</panel>

