<div slot="header">

**2. :fas-info-circle: [Suggestion] Add warning about Git in cloud-synced folders in Git Tour 1**
</div>

### Problem

Under [Week 2 > "Project" > Step 3: "Set up the project on your computer"](https://nus-cs2103-ay2526s1.github.io/website/schedule/week2/project.html#3-set-up-the-project-on-your-computer) point 3, there is a warning informing students to avoid placing Git-controlled stuff inside cloud-synced folders.

<img width="918" height="95" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/ce63eeff-a856-4451-bd12-e42cc8aee5ba" alt="Yellow warning exclamation mark symbol next to text saying Avoid putting Git-controlled files inside cloud-synced (e.g., OneDrive, Dropbox) folders. Reason: Multiple tools trying to detect/sync changes in the same folder can cause conflicts and unexpected behaviors. If you want to access project files from multiple computers, use Git to do that (rather than cloud syncing tools)." />

However, as far as I could find, this warning is not included in the [Git Learning Trail for Week 1](https://nus-cs2103-ay2526s1.github.io/website/schedule/week1/topics.html#W1-6).

Students are expected to (and likely will) view the Git Learning Trail for Week 1 (and 2) and do its corresponding hands-on activities before setting up the project and seeing the above warning on cloud-synced folders. As such, during the trail's hand-on activities, students may end up making Git-controlled files in their cloud-synced folders, unaware of potential issues.

### Proposed solution

Include this warning in the Git Learning Trail for Week 1 before any hands-on activities. The same warning can be cross-embedded/repeated in the Week 2 iP set-up instructions just in case students forget.

This will ensure that students do not do the Git hands-on activities in the Git Learning Trail in a cloud-synced folders.

_Edit: Fixed alt text issue with image. Disclosure: used GPT-5 mini in [duck.ai](https://duck.ai) to detect the mistake._
</panel>

<panel  popup-url="https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/67" expanded>
<div slot="header">

**3. :fas-info-circle: Policy on giving credit for IDE-generated code for constructors, getters/setters, etc.**
</div>



I understand from the [course website on the policy regarding reuse](https://nus-cs2103-ay2526s1.github.io/website/admin/appendixB-policies.html#giving-credit-for-reused-work) that we generally need to give credit for code reuse.

May I check if this also applies to straightforward code auto-generated by IDEs/other text editors, such as constructors, getters, setters, and toString() methods (for example, via the [IntellJ IDEA "Generate code" feature](https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/generating-code.html))? Do we need to give credit for such code and if so, how should we do so?

My impression is that, when first coding in Java, it is good to code such methods manually by hand to better understand them. But for those familiar with Java who have already manually typed out such methods many times, there seems to be little educational benefit to retype, say, a straightforward constructor or getter again. (Please correct me if I'm wrong! I recognise I'm not an expert on pedagogy.)

To be clear, I am not referring to code auto-generated by AI tools like Copilot. To the best of my knowledge, the aforementioned IDE/text editor features don't use what would typically be considered AI.
</panel>

</panel>


