I also encountered the same issue as you. Here is what I did:
- Added a flag to the program. I called it `--fresh`. This tells the program to start fresh, without loading memory. This allows for my UI tests to be predictable every time.
- I chose to test my save/load functionality using JUnit. Basically, I create a list of tasks, save it, load it and make sure the loaded tasks exactly matches the one that I created.
- I am maintaining both ways of testing for now. text-ui-test is excellent at testing expected UI outputs from the program, but cannot test the smaller functionalities/logic. On the other hand, JUnit is awesome at testing said logic but is cumbersome when utilised to test the UI outputs from the program.
</panel>

